{"parse":{"title":"milk","pageid":28717,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Milk}}\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{enPR|mĭlk}}, {{IPA|en|/mɪlk/}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-milk.ogg|a=UK}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-milk.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{IPA|en|[mɛlk]|a=Canada,Great Lakes,for some speakers|ref=Arden R. Thorum, ''Phonetics: A Contemporary Approach'' (2013), page 107}}\n* {{IPA|en|[milk]|a=Southern US,for some speakers}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɪlk|ɛlk|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*h₂melǵ-}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|milk}}, {{m|enm|mylk}}, {{m|enm|melk}}, {{m|enm|mulc}}, from {{inh|en|ang|meolc}}, {{m|ang|meoluc||milk}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*meluk||milk}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*meluks||milk}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₂melǵ-||milk, to milk}}.\n\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|fy|molke||milk}}, {{cog|nl|melk||milk}}, {{cog|nds-nl|melk||milk}}, {{cog|de|Milch||milk}}, {{cog|nds-de|Melk||milk}}, {{cog|yi|מילך||milk}}, {{cog|da|mælk||milk}}, {{cog|fo|-}} and {{cog|is|mjólk||milk}}, {{cog|nrn|*mjølk||milk}}, {{cog|nb|melk}}, {{m|nb|mjølk||milk}}, {{cog|nn|mjølk||milk}}, {{cog|sv|mjölk||milk}}, {{cog|got|𐌼𐌹𐌻𐌿𐌺𐍃||milk}}, {{cog|el|αμέλγω||to milk}}, {{cog|sq|mjel||to milk}}, {{cog|lv|malks}}, {{cog|lt|malkas}}, {{cog|be|малако́||milk}}, {{cog|bg|мля́ко||milk}}, {{cog|cs|mléko}}, {{cog|mk|мле́ко||milk}}, {{cog|pl|mleko||milk}}, {{cog|ru|-}} and {{cog|uk|молоко́||milk}}, {{cog|sh|mlijéko||milk}}, {{cog|sk|mlieko||milk}}, {{cog|sl|mlẹ́ko||milk}}, {{cog|cy|blith}}, {{cog|xto|malke}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n[[File:Milk glass.jpg|thumb|upright|A [[glass]] of cow's milk.]]\n[[File:Cow female black white.jpg|thumb|A [[dairy cow]]. Most, but not all, commercial milk production in the Western world is cow-based.]]\n# {{senseid|en|Q8495}}{{lb|en|uncountable}} A [[white]] [[liquid]] produced by the [[mammary gland]]s of [[female]] [[mammal]]s to nourish their [[young]]. From certain [[animal]]s, especially [[cows]], it is also called [[dairy milk]] and is a common food for [[human]]s as a [[beverage]] or used to produce various [[dairy product]]s such as [[butter]], [[cheese]], and [[yogurt]].\n#: {{syn|en|dairy milk|;|cowmilk|cow's milk|q2=often implied}}\n#: {{ux|en|Skyr is a product made of curdled '''milk'''.}}\n#* '''2007''' September 24, Chris Horseman (interviewee), Emily Harris (reporter), “Global Dairy Demand Drives Up Prices”, ''Morning Edition'', National Public Radio\n#*: {{...}}there's going to be that much less '''milk''' available to cover any other uses. Which means whether it's liquid '''milk''' or whether it's [milk that's been turned into] cheese or yogurt, the price gets pulled up right across the board.\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=A Brief History of Everyone Who Ever Lived|author=w:Adam Rutherford|year=2017|ISBN=9781615194049|publisher=The Experiment|passage=In the West it's' fairly normal to drink '''milk''' in various forms into adulthood.|page=75}}\n# {{senseid|en|white liquid from a vegetable source}} {{lb|en|uncountable|by extension}} A white (or whitish) [[liquid]] obtained from a [[vegetable]] source such as [[almond]]s, [[coconut]]s, [[oat]]s, [[rice]], or [[soy bean]]s.\n#: {{syn|en|m*lk|mylk|non-dairy milk|plant milk}}\n#: {{hypo|en|almond milk|coconut milk|hazelnut milk|hemp milk|oat milk|peanut milk|rice milk|soy milk}}\n#* {{quote-web|en|url=http://www.theguardian.com/food/2018/sep/17/milk-mania-why-most-alternatives-arent-great-but-camel-milk-just-might-be|title='Milk' mania: why most alternatives aren't great – but camel milk just might be|date=2018-09-16|author=Alexandra Spring|work=The Guardian|passage=Where it does fall down, however, is its nutritional value. While oats are largely a healthy grain to include in your diet, the '''milk''' is highly diluted with water, giving it little nutritional value.}}\n#* {{quote-web|en|url=http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/jan/28/what-plant-milk-should-i-drink-almond-killing-bees-aoe|title=Almonds are out. Dairy is a disaster. So what milk should we drink?|date=2020-01-29|author=Annette McGivney|work=The Guardian|passage=For environmentally minded consumers, the news is hard to swallow: almond '''milk''' is not healthy for the planet and the popular milk substitute is especially hard on bees.}}\n# {{lb|en|countable|informal}} An individual [[serving]] of milk.\n#: {{ux|en|Table three ordered three '''milks'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|countable|or|invariant}} An individual [[portion]] of milk, such as found in a [[creamer]], for tea and coffee.\n#: {{ux|en|I take my tea with two '''milks''' and two sugars.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I take my tea with two '''milk''' and two sugar.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2014|author=Don Eggspuehler|title=Teachings From Pop|publisher=Author House|isbn=9781496907202|page=459\n|passage=She just sat there drinking cup after cup of strong coffee, with two '''milks''' and two sugars.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2015|author=Carolyn Arnold|title=City of Gold: (Mathew Connor Adventure Series Book 1)|publisher=Hibbert & Stiles Publishing Inc.|isbn=9781988353043\n|passage=Five minutes later, he returned with Justin&#39;s large coffee with two '''milk''' and two sweeteners and a black coffee for himself.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2019|author=Maggie Blackbird|title=Redeemed: The Matawapit Family Series, #1|publisher=eXtasy Books|isbn=9781487424558|page=349\n|passage=Mrs. Dale huffed up to the counter and fired her battle-axe stare at the attendant. “One medium tea. ... Two double-doubles, and one with two '''milk''' and two  sweeteners.”}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2020|author=John Mitton|title=Tedmund and the Murdered Heiress|publisher=Page Publishing, Inc|isbn=9781645846505\n|passage=She placed on her desk a brown paper bag; it held her breakfast, cream cheese on a toasted bagel and coffee with two '''milks''' and one sugar.}}\n# The ripe, undischarged [[spat]] of an [[oyster]].\n# {{lb|en|uncountable|vulgar|slang}} [[semen|Semen]].\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* Following a [[European Union]] (EU) court ruling in 2017, the term ''milk'' cannot legally be used to market purely plant-based products ({{senseno|en|white liquid from a vegetable source}}) in the EU.<ref>{{cite-web|url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/HTML/?uri=CELEX:62016CJ0422&from=EN|date=14 June 2017|work=EUR-Lex|title=Judgment of the Court (Seventh Chamber) of 14 June 2017|passage=The term ‘milk’ shall mean exclusively the normal mammary secretion obtained from one or more milkings without either addition thereto or extraction therefrom.}}</ref>\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col3|en|acid of milk|wild mare's milk\n|African milk barrel\n|African milk tree\n|age like milk\n|almondmilk\n|almond milk\n|almond-milk\n|Amazon milk frog\n|antimilk\n|Aval Milk\n|baby milk\n|boob milk\n|bread and milk\n|breakfast milk\n|breast milk\n|buttermilk\n|cashew milk|Milk Snatcher\n|cat milk\n|Channel Island milk|milk treading|poppy milk\n|chocolate milk\n|choco milk\n|coconut milk\n|coffee milk\n|condensed milk\n|cowmilk,cow milk,cow's milk\n|crop milk\n|cry over spilt milk,cry over spilled milk\n|dick milk\n|dog milk|milk of sulfur|silk-stocking milk tea\n|don't cry over spilled milk\n|don't teach your grandmother how to milk ducks\n|dried milk\n|dysphoric milk ejection reflex\n|evaporated milk\n|filled milk\n|first milk\n|flavored milk,flavoured milk\n|flax milk\n|fore-milk\n|foremilk\n|full cream milk\n|glacial milk\n|glacier milk\n|goatmilk,goat milk,goat's milk\n|goat's milk cheese\n|goat's-milk cheese\n|golden milk\n|gold-top milk\n|green milk\n|hazelnut milk\n|hemp milk\n|hindmilk\n|hold my milk\n|homogenized milk,homo milk\n|horsemilk,horse milk\n|hot milk cake\n|hot-milk cake\n|human milk\n|ice milk,iced milk\n|land of milk and honey\n|lapper-milk\n|litmus milk\n|low-fat milk\n|malted milk\n|man-milk\n|man milk\n|mare's milk\n|mild as milk\n|milk abscess\n|milk acid\n|milkaholic,milkoholic\n|milk albuminate\n|milk-alkali syndrome\n|milk-and-water\n|milk-and-wateriness\n|milk-and-watery\n|milkbag\n|milk bar\n|milk-bar cowboy\n|milk before meat\n|milkborne\n|milk bottle\n|milkbox\n|milkboy\n|milk bread\n|milk brother,milk-brother\n|milkbush\n|milk camel\n|milk can\n|milk-cap,milk cap,milkcap\n|milk caps\n|milk card\n|milk carton\n|milk chocolate\n|milk churn\n|milk cow\n|milk crate\n|milkcrate\n|milk crust\n|milk delivery door\n|milk dentition\n|milk door\n|milk drinker\n|milk-drunk\n|milk duct\n|milken\n|milkery\n|milk factory\n|milkfat,milk fat\n|milkfed,milk-fed\n|milk fever\n|milk fiber\n|milk fibre\n|milkfish\n|milk float\n|milk food\n|milk-free\n|milk fruit\n|milkful\n|milk glass\n|milk gravy\n|milk hedge\n|milkhouse,milk-house,milk house\n|milk ice\n|milkie\n|milkiness\n|milkish\n|milk jug\n|milk knot\n|milk leg\n|milkless\n|milklike\n|milk line\n|milk-livered\n|milk-maid\n|milkmaid\n|milkmaiden\n|milk-maker\n|milk maker\n|milkman\n|milk mirror\n|milk monitor\n|milk moon\n|milk mother,milk-mother\n|milk moustache\n|milk mustache\n|milko\n|milk of amnesia\n|milk of human kindness\n|milk of lime\n|milk of magnesia\n|milk of roses\n|Milkomeda,Milkdromeda\n|milk pan\n|milkpan\n|milk parsley\n|milk pea\n|milkperson\n|milk powder\n|milkpox\n|milk product\n|milk pudding\n|milk punch\n|milk replacer\n|milk roll\n|milk round\n|milk run\n|milk-sap\n|milk saucepan\n|milk scall\n|milkshake,milk-shake,milk shake\n|milkshed\n|milk sibling,milk-sibling\n|milk sickness\n|milksicle\n|milk sister,milk-sister\n|milk skin\n|milk snake,milksnake\n|milksop\n|milksoppery\n|milksoppish\n|milksoppy\n|milk spot\n|milkstache\n|milkstain\n|milkstained\n|milkstone\n|milk stout\n|milk substitute\n|milk sugar\n|milk sweet\n|milk tea\n|milk the clock\n|milk thistle\n|milk toast\n|milktoast\n|milk token\n|milk tongue\n|milk tooth,milk-tooth\n|milk train\n|milktree\n|milk truck\n|milk tusk\n|milkvetch,milk-vetch,milk vetch\n|milk voucher\n|milk-warm\n|milkweed\n|milk-white,milkwhite\n|milkwoman\n|milkwood\n|milk wool\n|milkwort\n|milky\n|Milky Way\n|moonmilk\n|moon milk\n|moose milk\n|mother's milk\n|mountain milk\n|mylk\n|neonatal milk\n|nonmilk\n|nut milk\n|oat milk\n|one-percent milk,1% milk\n|overmilk\n|pale as milk\n|peanut milk\n|pigeon milk,pigeon's milk\n|pilk\n|plant milk\n|powdered milk\n|premilk\n|producer milk\n|raw milk\n|reduced-fat milk\n|rice milk\n|saffron milk cap\n|semi-skimmed milk\n|share milk\n|share-milk\n|sharemilk\n|sheep milk\n|skimmed milk,skim milk\n|soured milk\n|sour milk\n|soy milk\n|soymilk\n|soy milk maker\n|spilt milk\n|sugar of milk\n|sweet milk\n|swill milk\n|that accounts for the milk in the coconut\n|there's no point crying over spilt milk\n|there's no use crying over spilt milk\n|three-milk cake\n|tiger's milk\n|two-percent milk,2% milk\n|ugly milk-cap\n|UHT milk\n|undermilk\n|unmilky\n|whole milk\n|why buy the cow when you can get the milk for free\n|witches' milk\n|witch's milk\n|wolf's milk,wolf's-milk\n}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|en|milch}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n{{top3}}\n* {{desc|crp-slb|милекъ}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|chk|minik}}\n* {{desc|der=1|kld|milambaraay}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|gil|miriki}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|iso|imiliki}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|ja|ミルク|tr=miruku}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|ko|밀크}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|ln|míliki}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|mi|miraka}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|mh|milik}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|vo|milig}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|yo|mílíìkì}}\n{{bottom}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{see translation subpage|Noun}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n[[File:StateLibQld 1 153895 Milking the cow at Ambrose&#039;s farm, Raglan, 1912.jpg|thumb|Milking a cow at an Australian farm in 1912]]\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|milken}}, from {{inh|en|ang|melcan}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*melkaną}}, ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₂melǵ-}}, the same root as the noun. Compare {{cog|nl|-}} and {{cog|de|melken}}, {{cog|da|malke}}, {{cog|no|mjølke}}, also {{cog|la|mulgeō||to milk}}, {{cog|grc|ἀμέλγω||to milk}}, {{cog|sq|mjel||to milk}}, {{cog|ru|молоко́}}, {{cog|lt|mélžti}}, {{cog|xto|mālk-}}.\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[express]] milk from (a mammal, especially a [[cow]]).\n#: {{ux|en|The farmer '''milked''' his cows.}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Macbeth|I|vii|135|2|passage=I haue giuen Sucke, and know / How tender 'tis to loue the Babe that '''milkes''' me{{...}}}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|intransitive}} To draw (milk) from the breasts or udder.\n#: {{ux|en|to '''milk''' wholesome milk from healthy cows}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|transitive|rare}} To secrete (milk) from the breasts or udder.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1890|author=James George Frazer|title=The Golden Bough|volume=2|page=84|text=The black cow '''milking''' white milk, black hen on the nest laying white eggs.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[express]] a [[liquid]] from a [[creature]].\n#: {{ux|en|The [[Australia]]n government has a team that regularly '''milks''' various [[snake]]s for [[venom]] to use creating [[serum]]s and [[antivenom]]s.}}\n#* {{quote-av|en|year=1966|director={{w|Bruce Brown (director)|Bruce Brown}}|title={{w|The Endless Summer}}|text=He captures animals for zoos around the world... and '''milks''' cobra snakes for their venom.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|figurative}} To make excessive use of (a particular point in speech or writing, a source of funds, etc.); to [[exploit]]; to [[take advantage of]] (something).\n#: {{ux|en|When the audience began laughing, the comedian '''milked''' the joke for more laughs.}}\n#* '''July 21, 1877''', \"The Block in the Courts\" in ''The Spectator''\n#*: They [the lawyers] '''milk''' an unfortunate estate as regularly as a dairyman does his stock.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Daniel Taylor|title=Lucas Moura double for Spurs deepens gloom at Manchester United| work={{w|The Guardian}} (London)| date=27 August 2018| url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/aug/27/manchester-united-tottenham-hotspur-premier-league-match-report| passage=If nothing else, {{w|José Mourinho}} can be grateful there was no mutiny. He still heard his name being sung and at the final whistle {{w|Old Trafford}} was not too unkind on the manager or his players. He '''milked''' it, too, marching over to the Stretford End to thank them for their generosity.}}\n# {{lb|en|of an electrical storage battery}} To give off small [[gas]] [[bubble]]s during the final part of the [[charge|charging]] operation.\n# {{lb|en|transitive|BDSM|vulgar}} To masturbate a male to ejaculation, especially for the amusement or satisfaction of the masturbator rather than the person masturbated.\n#: {{syn|en|masturbate}}\n#: {{ux|en|Controlled '''milking''' can actually establish and consolidate a mistress’s dominance over her sub rather than diminish it.}}\n#* {{quote-book |en |year=2015 |author=Joyce Snyder |title=Mistress Pussycat: Adventures with Submissive Men in the World of Femdom |publisher=Headpress |isbn=978-1-909394-26-1 |passage=“No, no, no! When a male is in ''chas-ti-ty,''” (Clive always drew out this word and also ''slavery'', emphasizing every syllable to give it extra importance) “he should receive regular '''milking''' to maintain good hygiene.” (Yet more kinky behavior cloaked as healthy living.) “'''Milking''' helps flush out the toxins which accumulate within the prostate gland of a chaste male.”}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en\n|milk the clock\n|milkable\n|milker\n|milking\n|milking machine\n|milking table\n|remilk\n|unmilkable\n|unmilked\n}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|to express milk from mammal}}\n* Abkhaz: {{t|ab|ахьара}}\n* Afar: {{t|aa|han}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|melk}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|mjel}}, {{t|sq|mîl}}, {{t+|sq|mjel}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|حَلَبَ}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{t|ary|حلب|tr=ḥlab}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Classical Syriac: {{t|syc|ܚܠܒ|tr=ḥəlaḇ}}\n*: Western Neo-Aramaic: {{t|arc|ܐܚܠܒ|tr=eḥlab}}\n* Archi: {{t|aqc|ацас}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|կթել}}\n* Aromanian: {{t|rup|mulgu}}, {{t|rup|lãptuescu}}\n* Assamese: {{t|as|খিৰোৱা}}\n* Avar: {{t|av|бечӏчӏизе}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t|az|sağmaq}}\n* Basque: {{t|eu|jetzi}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|даі́ць|impf}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|доя́|impf}}\n* Buryat: {{t|bua|һааха}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|munyir}}\n* Cebuano: {{t|ceb|gatasan}}\n* Chechen: {{t|ce|детта}}\n* Chichewa: {{t|ny|kama|alt=-kama}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|擠奶|tr=jǐnǎi}}, {{t+|cmn|產乳|tr=chǎnrǔ}}\n* Comorian:\n*: Ngazidja Comorian: {{t|zdj|hama|alt=uhama}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|dojit|impf}}, {{t|cs|podojit|pf}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|malke}}\n* Dolgan: {{t|dlg|ыак}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|melken}}\n* Erzya: {{t|myv|потявтомс}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|melki}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|lüpsma}}\n* Even: {{t|eve|хир-}}\n* Faroese: {{t|fo|mjólka}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|lypsää}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|traire}}\n* Friulian: {{t|fur|molgi}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|muxir}}\n* German: {{t+|de|melken}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|αρμέγω}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|ἀμέλγω}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|חָלַב|tr=khaláv}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|fej|id=to milk}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|melkar}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|susu}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|crúigh}}, {{t|ga|bligh}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|mungere}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|[[乳]]を[[搾る]]|tr=ちちをしぼる, chichi o shiboru}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|сауу}}\n* Korean: {{t|ko|[[젖]][[-을]] [[짜다]]}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Central Kurdish: {{t|ckb|دۆشین}}\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{t+|kmr|doşîn}}, {{t+|kmr|dotin}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{t|ky|саа}}\n* Lao:  {{t-needed|lo}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|mulgeō}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|slaukt}}\n* Lezgi: {{t|lez|ацун}}\n* Lombard: {{t|lmo|móng}}, {{t|lmo|mung}}\n* Low German:\n*: German Low German: {{t|nds-de|melken}}\n* Luxembourgish: {{t|lb|sträichen}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|молзе|impf}}\n* Malay: {{t+|ms|perah}}, {{t+|ms|susu}}\n* Maltese: {{t|mt|ħaleb}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|kutētē}}, {{t|mi|whakatētē}}\n* Mongolian: {{t+|mn|саах}}\n* Nanai: {{t|gld|сири-}}\n* Nepali: {{t|ne|दुहुनु}}\n* Norman: {{t|nrf|traithe}}\n* Northern Altai: {{t|atv|сагарга}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|melke}}, {{t|nb|mjølke}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t|nn|mjølke}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|mólzer}}\n* Old Church Slavonic:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|cu|доити|impf}}\n* Old East Slavic: {{t